[30;1m384 | [0m[35m to be aware of the following.[0m
[30;1m385 | [0m[35m    The wire protocol is text based so serpent has to encode any binary data. It uses base-64 to do [0m
[30;1m386 | [0m[35m    This means on the receiving side, instead of the raw bytes, you get a little dictionary[0m
[30;1m387 | [0m[35m    like this instead: ``{'data': 'aXJtZW4gZGUgam9uZw==', 'encoding': 'base64'}``[0m
[30;1m388 | [0m[35m    Your client code needs to be aware of this and to get the original binary data back, it has to b[0m
[30;1m389 | [0m[35m    decode the data element by itself.  This is perhaps done the easiest by using the[0m
[30;1m390 | [0m[35m    ``serpent.tobytes`` helper function from the ``serpent`` library, which will convert[0m

[30;1m78 | [0m[35m**Using SSL/TLS**[0m
[30;1m79 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m80 | [0m[35mEnable it by setting the ``SSL`` config item to True, and configure the other SSL config items[0m
[30;1m81 | [0m[35mas required. You'll need to specify the cert files to use, private keys, and passwords if any.[0m
[30;1m82 | [0m[35mBy default, the SSL mode only has a cert on the server (which is similar to visiting a https url[0m
[30;1m83 | [0m[35min your browser). This means your *clients* can be sure that they are connecting to the expected[0m
[30;1m84 | [0m[35mserver, but the *server* has no way to know what clients are connecting.[0m

[30;1m68 | [0m[35m================================[0m

[30;1m339 | [0m[35mThe PYRONAME protocol type[0m
[30;1m340 | [0m[35m==========================[0m
[30;1m341 | [0m[35mTo create a proxy and connect to a Pyro object, Pyro needs an URI so it can find the object.[0m
[30;1m342 | [0m[35mBecause it is so convenient, the name server logic has been integrated into Pyro's URI mechanism[0m
[30;1m343 | [0m[35mby means of the special ``PYRONAME`` protocol type (rather than the normal ``PYRO`` protocol type).[0m
[30;1m344 | [0m[35mThis protocol type tells Pyro to treat the URI as a logical object name instead, and Pyro will[0m

[30;1m294 | [0m[35mPyro behind a NAT router/firewall[0m
[30;1m295 | [0m[35m=================================[0m
[30;1m296 | [0m[35mYou can run Pyro behind a NAT router/firewall.[0m
[30;1m297 | [0m[35mAssume the external hostname is 'pyro.server.com' and the external port is 5555.[0m
[30;1m298 | [0m[35mAlso assume the internal host is 'server1.lan' and the internal port is 9999.[0m
[30;1m299 | [0m[35mYou'll need to have a NAT rule that maps pyro.server.com:5555 to server1.lan:9999.[0m
[30;1m300 | [0m[35mYou'll need to start your Pyro daemon, where you specify the ``nathost`` and ``natport`` arguments,[0m

[30;1m448 | [0m[35mIt is possible to get data transfer speeds that are close to the limit of your network adapter[0m
[30;1m449 | [0m[35mby doing the actual data transfer via low-level socket code and everything else via Pyro.[0m
[30;1m450 | [0m[35mThis keeps the amount of low-level code to a minimum.[0m
[30;1m451 | [0m[35mHave a look at the ``filetransfer`` example again, to see a possible way of doing this.[0m
[30;1m452 | [0m[35mIt creates a special Daemon subclass that uses Pyro for everything as usual,[0m
[30;1m453 | [0m[35mbut for actual file transfer it sets up a dedicated temporary socket connection over which the file [0m
[30;1m454 | [0m[35mis transmitted.[0m

[30;1m434 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m435 | [0m[35mPyro allows you to add custom annotation chunks to the request and response messages[0m
[30;1m436 | [0m[35m(see  :ref:`msg_annotations`). Because these are binary chunks they will not be passed[0m
[30;1m437 | [0m[35mthrough the serializer at all. There is a 64Kb total annotation size limit on messages[0m
[30;1m438 | [0m[35mthough, so you have to split up larger files. The ``filetransfer`` example contains[0m
[30;1m439 | [0m[35mfully working example code to see this in action. It combines this with the remote[0m
[30;1m440 | [0m[35miterator capability of Pyro to easily get all chunks of the file.[0m

[30;1m150 | [0m[35mMultiple network interfaces[0m
[30;1m151 | [0m[35m===========================[0m
[30;1m152 | [0m[35mThis is a difficult subject but here are a few short notes about it.[0m
[30;1m153 | [0m[35m*At this time, Pyro doesn't support running on multiple network interfaces at the same time*.[0m
[30;1m154 | [0m[35mYou can bind a deamon on INADDR_ANY (0.0.0.0) though, including the name server.[0m
[30;1m155 | [0m[35mBut weird things happen with the URIs of objects published through these servers, because they[0m
[30;1m156 | [0m[35mwill point to 0.0.0.0 and your clients won't be able to connect to the actual objects.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m295[0m[34m of [0m[33m685[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000600[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Windows[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m
  Filename: [33m/Pyro4-4.82/docs/source/tipstricks.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m\s(advpack\.dll|appvlp|at|atbroker|bash|bginfo|bitsadmin|cdb|certutil|cl_invocation\.ps1|cl_mutexverifiers\.ps1|cmd|cmdkey|cmstp|comsvcs\.dll|control|csc|cscript|csi|devtoolslauncher|dfsvc|diskshadow|dnscmd|dnx|dotnet|dxcap|esentutl|eventvwr|excel|expand|extexport|extrac32|findstr|forfiles|ftp|gfxdownloadwrapper|gpscript|hh|ie4uinit|ieadvpack\.dll|ieaframe\.dll|ic|infdefaultinstall|installutil|jsc|makecab|manage-bde\.wsf|mavinject|mftrace|microsoft\.workflow\.compiler|mmc|msbuild|msconfig|msdeploy|msdt|mshta|mshtml\.dll|msc|msxsl|netsh|odbcconf|pcalua|pcwrun|pcwutl\.dll|pester\.bat|powerpnt|presentationhost|pubprn\.vbs|rcsi|reg|regasm|regedit|register-cimprovider|regsvcs|regsvr32|rpcping|rundll32|runonce|runscripthelper|sc|schtasks|scriptrunner|setupapi\.dll|shdocvw\.dll|shell32\.dll|slmgr\.vbs|sqldumper|sqlps|sqltoolsps|squirrel|syncappvpublishingserver|syncappvpublishingserver\.vbs|syssetup\.dll|te|tracker|tttracer|update|url\.dll|verclsid|vsjitdebugger|wab|winrm\.vbs|winword|wmic|wscript|wsl|wsreset|xwizard|zipfldr\.dll)\s[0m
[30;1m142 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m143 | [0m[35mThe various logger names are similar to the module that uses the logger,[0m
[30;1m144 | [0m[35mso for instance logging done by code in ``Pyro4.core`` will use a logger category name of ``Pyro4.co[0m
[30;1m145 | [0m[35mLook at the top of the source code of the various modules from Pyro to see what the exact names are.[0m
[30;1m146 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m147 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m148 | [0m[35m.. index:: multiple NICs, network interfaces[0m

[30;1m157 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m158 | [0m[35mThe name server however contains a little trick. The broadcast responder can also be bound on 0.0.0.[0m
[30;1m159 | [0m[35mand it will in fact try to determine the correct ip address of the interface that a client needs to [0m

[30;1m696 | [0m[35mDue to internal locking you can freely share proxies among threads.[0m
[30;1m697 | [0m[35mThe lock makes sure that only a single thread is actually using the proxy's[0m
[30;1m698 | [0m[35mcommunication channel at all times.[0m
[30;1m699 | [0m[35mThis can be convenient *but* it may not be the best way to approach things. The lock essentially[0m
[30;1m700 | [0m[35mprevents parallelism. If you want calls to go in parallel, give each thread its own proxy.[0m

[30;1m349 | [0m[35m=============[0m
[30;1m350 | [0m[35mDoing many small remote method calls in sequence has a fair amount of latency and overhead.[0m
[30;1m351 | [0m[35mPyro provides a means to gather all these small calls and submit it as a single 'batched call'.[0m
[30;1m352 | [0m[35mWhen the server processed them all, you get back all results at once.[0m
[30;1m353 | [0m[35mDepending on the size of the arguments, the network speed, and the amount of calls,[0m
[30;1m354 | [0m[35mdoing a batched call can be *much* faster than invoking every call by itself.[0m
[30;1m355 | [0m[35mNote that this feature is only available for calls on the same proxy object.[0m

[30;1m619 | [0m[35mTimeouts[0m
[30;1m620 | [0m[35m--------[0m
[30;1m621 | [0m[35mBecause calls on Pyro objects go over the network, you might encounter network related problems that[0m
[30;1m622 | [0m[35mdon't have when using normal objects. One possible problems is some sort of network hiccup[0m
[30;1m623 | [0m[35mthat makes your call unresponsive because the data never arrived at the server or the response never[0m
[30;1m624 | [0m[35marrived back to the caller.[0m
[30;1m625 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m714 | [0m[35m    double: server type; what to choose?[0m
[30;1m715 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m716 | [0m[35m*When to choose which server type?*[0m
[30;1m717 | [0m[35mWith the threadpool server at least you have a chance to achieve concurrency, and[0m

[30;1m719 | [0m[35mtrouble with using threads in Python still applies though:[0m
[30;1m720 | [0m[35mPython threads don't run concurrently unless they release the :abbr:`GIL (Global Interpreter Lock)`.[0m

[30;1m700 | [0m[35m    all remote method calls sequentially. No threads are used in this server.[0m
[30;1m701 | [0m[35m    It uses the best supported selector available on your platform (kqueue, poll, select).[0m
